    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d825a4fb8f4417045815f4c921aa0cc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 357343,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 697449,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/697449/paul-bellora",
                "reputation": 55381,
                "display_name": "Paul Bellora",
                "accept_rate": 82
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1344486823,
            "creation_date": 1344485295,
            "body": "<p>It sounds like you want to use a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Set.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Set<\/code><\/a> implementation. If order doesn't matter, just use <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/HashSet.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>HashSet<\/code><\/a>. If you want to keep insertion-order, use <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/LinkedHashSet.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>LinkedHashSet<\/code><\/a>. Or, to maintain natural ordering, use <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/TreeSet.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>TreeSet<\/code><\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>In any case, make sure to override your element object's <code>equals<\/code> method. What you have is a good start. After checking <code>in instanceof UniqueFruits<\/code>, cast <code>in<\/code> to <code>UniqueFruits<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>UniqueFruits uf = (UniqueFruits)in;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You can then check each relevant field using <code>equals<\/code> in turn (make sure to check for <code>null<\/code> first if a field is nullable). Any modern IDE will help you generate <code>equals<\/code> automatically. It may be educational to try it yourself first, then compare with the generated version.<\/p>\n\n<p>Make sure to override <code>hashCode<\/code> also (IDEs will similarly help you with this, and there is plenty of reading online about the matter - just search).<\/p>\n\n<p>If you use <code>TreeSet<\/code> (or some other <code>SortedSet<\/code> implementation), your element object should either implement <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Comparable.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Comparable<\/code><\/a> or else you should provide the <code>SortedSet<\/code> with a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Comparator.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Comparator<\/code><\/a>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876671,
            "question_id": 11876605,
            "last_edit_date": 1344486823
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2f852a4e36a4222fc16f4834537beca4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1196838,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1168372,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1168372/sujay",
                "reputation": 6781,
                "display_name": "Sujay",
                "accept_rate": 79
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344485818,
            "creation_date": 1344485264,
            "body": "<p>I would suggest using <code>Set<\/code> instead of <code>ArrayList<\/code> for storing unique elements. It is easier and cleaner.<\/p>\n\n<p>As per the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/Set.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">javadoc<\/a> for <code>Set<\/code>, here's what it says:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>A collection that contains no duplicate elements. More formally, sets\n  contain no pair of elements e1 and e2 such that e1.equals(e2), and at\n  most one null element. As implied by its name, this interface models\n  the mathematical set abstraction<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Here's an <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/203984/how-do-i-remove-repeated-elements-from-arraylist\">SO article<\/a> that talks about how to remove repeated elements from <code>ArrayList<\/code>. However, you would notice that most of the solutions provided uses an implementation of <code>Set<\/code> to achieve what you want to do. In any case, over-riding <code>equals()<\/code> as you've done will not help achieve your objective. <em>If it's not too much of a trouble (I don't understand why you need to stick with an <code>ArrayList<\/code> given your actual requirement, I would <strong>strongly<\/strong> suggest moving to a <code>Set<\/code> implementation.<\/em><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876668,
            "question_id": 11876605,
            "last_edit_date": 1495535078
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f1a6a2ca986c681283a050a1fa74ce33?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 263814,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 549643,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/549643/patton",
                "reputation": 2052,
                "display_name": "Patton",
                "accept_rate": 96
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344485393,
            "creation_date": 1344485393,
            "body": "<p>If your fruitname class has 2 attributes, like <code>fruitname<\/code> and <code>fruitclass<\/code> then<\/p>\n\n<p>your check code should be<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>UniqueFruits current = (UniqueFruits) in;\nif(this.fruitname.equals(current.fruitname) &amp;&amp; this.fruitclass.equals(current.fruitclass)) {\n  return true;\n}else{\n   return false;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And coming to hashcode ask your IDE to generate the hasdcode for <code>UniqueFruits<\/code> Class.\nAnd use <code>Set<\/code> instead of <code>ArrayList<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>On a lighter note Your IDE can even generate equals() for you.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876690,
            "question_id": 11876605
        }
